    "library.back":"← Back to home","library.pageName":"Technical content","library.eyebrow":"Technical knowledge","library.title":"Technical information for better-informed decisions.","library.intro":"Introductory content on diagnostics, uprating feasibility and digital integration applied to transformer engineering.","library.indexTitle":"On this page","library.otherTitle":"Technical content","library.takeaway":"Key point","library.hubEyebrow":"Technical library","library.hubTitle":"Explore the available content.","library.hubText":"Each resource has its own page to make reading, sharing and future reference easier.","library.card1Text":"Diagnostics, dedicated design and traceability as foundations of a technically sound repair.","library.card2Text":"The data and subsystems that must be assessed before proposing any increase in capacity.","library.card3Text":"How structured data, parametric models and governance connect engineering development.",
    "library.a1lead":"A technically sound repair begins by understanding the equipment and its history, not by simply replacing the part that failed.","library.a1h1":"Diagnosis comes before intervention","library.a1p1":"Operating history, inspection, construction survey and applicable tests provide a basis for assessing transformer subsystems. Results must be analyzed together: a single indication, in isolation, does not define the solution.","library.a1h2":"Each piece of equipment requires its own design","library.a1p2":"The decision to reuse, restore or replace components depends on electrical, thermal, dielectric and mechanical compatibility. When characteristics change, calculations, materials, clearances, cooling and stresses must be reviewed according to the application and contractual requirements.","library.a1h3":"Traceability is also part of repair","library.a1p3":"Drawings, specifications, implemented changes, inspections, tests and final documentation should form a coherent technical history. This reduces future ambiguity and improves operation and maintenance decisions.","library.a1take":"Engineering-based repair means diagnosing, designing, executing, verifying and documenting — always according to the actual condition of the equipment.",
    "library.a2lead":"Uprating is not an automatic consequence of repair. It is an engineering decision that depends on the duty cycle, equipment condition and the limitations of each subsystem.","library.a2h1":"What information must be included in the assessment?","library.a2p1":"Target rating, load profile, ambient temperature, operating cycle, cooling system, event history and material condition are essential inputs. Without this context, there is no sound basis for proposing an increase in capacity.","library.a2h2":"Verification must be multidisciplinary","library.a2p2":"The assessment may involve electromagnetic performance, temperature rise, hot-spot temperature, insulation system, short-circuit stresses, tank, radiators, bushings, tap changing, protection and accessories. Overall feasibility is limited by the most critical subsystem.","library.a2h3":"The result may differ from the desired increase","library.a2p3":"A responsible assessment may conclude that the original rating should be maintained, that an increase is conditional on modifications, or that uprating is not feasible. There is no generic percentage that can be applied to every transformer.","library.a2take":"Service-life extension and any increase in capacity must be confirmed by design, acceptance criteria and tests compatible with the scope.",
    "library.a3lead":"Digital integration is not merely the production of a three-dimensional model. Real value appears when parameters, documents and revisions remain consistent throughout development.","library.a3h1":"A structured source for engineering data","library.a3p1":"Organized electrical and mechanical parameters can feed sizing rules and reduce data re-entry. The model should maintain a clear link to assumptions, versions and the people responsible for changes.","library.a3h2":"From the model to manufacturing documents","library.a3p2":"In a well-implemented workflow, parametric models support the generation of views, drawings and bills of materials. CAD APIs can also automate repetitive tasks, but rules and validation remain under engineering responsibility.","library.a3h3":"Automation requires control","library.a3p3":"Automation without governance only accelerates inconsistencies. Component libraries, revision criteria, version identification and technical checks are necessary to keep calculation, CAD, 3D and BOM synchronized.","library.a3take":"Technology creates value when it preserves engineering criteria, reduces repetitive tasks and improves decision traceability.",
    "library.sourcesTitle":"References and limitations","library.disclaimer":"This material is introductory and does not replace diagnostics, design, testing, contractual requirements or the standards applicable to each piece of equipment.","library.ctaTitle":"Does your equipment require an individual assessment?","library.ctaText":"Share the application and the available information for a technical conversation."
